Scott Goehring writes:
> 
> Same thing.  Both suggestions favor entrenching power in the hands of
> people who are good at gathering power.  You suggest a positive
> feedback loop, which, as anyone who does systems control knows, will
> force the system into the most extreme state possible over time.

Still, there are some positive reinforcement loops which could be 
interesting to simulate in Nomic. I am particularly fascinated by the
bank confidence paradox.

If a bank is going to lose a lot of money, people will take their money
out to avoid losing it. If a lot of people do this, the bank will collapse.
Thus, the belief that a bank is going to collapse is a self-fulfilling 
one, as long as it gains a certain critical threshhold. It would appear
that this is a positive feedback loop, but with more than one attractor.

I might re-propose my amendment to the Rebellion rules, to see what 
the current Nomic populace think of it. The idea behind them was to
make Rebellion a two-attractor positive feedback problem. 

Basically, the more people involved in a Rebellion, the more likely it
should be to succeed. And it should always profit players to be on the
winning side of a Rebellion. So there are two attractors. 

If no-one is rebelling, then a Rebellion is likely to fail, so players
are encouraged not to rebel.

If everyone is rebelling then a Rebellion is likely to succeed, so players
are encouraged to rebel.

If about half of the players are Rebelling, then we have a rather 
curious situation, where political influences will hold sway. If you 
can convince people the Rebellion is likely to succeed/fail, then you will
increase the chances of your prophecy being true.

I might dig out the old proto and re-post it.

